<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="504" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,151,611]" pageId="3" pageNumber="504">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,478,503]" pageId="3" pageNumber="504">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific name is from the Latin adjective “altus”, meaning “high”, and refers to the high insertion of the antenna.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="504" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,151,611]" pageId="3" pageNumber="504">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,550,575]" pageId="3" pageNumber="504">Remarks.</emphasis>
In Emden’s (1951) key to 
<taxonomicName box="[612,750,551,575]" class="Insecta" family="Muscidae" genus="Limnophora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="504" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[612,750,551,575]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="504">Limnophora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the new species runs to 
<taxonomicName authority="Emden" authorityName="Emden" box="[1029,1245,550,575]" class="Insecta" family="Muscidae" genus="Limnophora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="504" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pluripila">
<emphasis box="[1029,1156,551,575]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="504">L. pluripila</emphasis>
Emden
</taxonomicName>
, which is a small and entirely fuscous species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
